It has raised some suspicions in the West, and especially in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-built shopping malls and "power bakeries" where middle-class managers in business suit - men and women - meet in the early morning to make a deal.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
“The aim of the party’s foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he says.
Turkey has been cut off in relations with its interior.
Today you have to look at the East and the West at the same time.
It is not a case if it is not towards one or the other.
You have to do both.
"But surely at some point," I ask him, "could Turkey be forced to choose?"
"Turkey," he replies, "does not want to back that choice."
Next, underline a point that almost all of the people I have spoken to so far had almost recalled to me: the relations that Turkey has not only with the Middle East, but with the Caucasus region, and with the entire Black Sea, represent a benefit for Europe and the United States as well as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically assemble those railway lines that open the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Again to the Hydarpasha station, after a second sleepless night, my thought goes back to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building, 100 years ago.
How surprised would you be to know that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East, in large part, would be in Turkey’s hands today?
