The ‘Bee Car’ That Prevents Collisions
To advance the development of technologies for the prevention of accidents Nissan has been inspired, this time, in nature, specifically, in bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Center at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C is presented as an expansion of Nissan’s four-area Security Shield.
This robot intends to strengthen the collision prevention capability of the brand’s vehicles.
During its flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that looks a lot like the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important are the bee’s compound eyes, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing you to fly without interruption within your own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers designed what they have called a Laser Range Finder.
This detects obstacles that are up to two meters away within a 180 degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to said object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor that immediately results in collision prevention.
"The moment you detect an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a straight angle or greater to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the escape maneuver is entirely instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be deflected upwards or downwards or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like the bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
“This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act according to that data.
It does not require storing information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise, but we’re not talking about memory gigs, not even megas.”
This is the first step in developing new collision-instant prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan Vatican will introduce to standard cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination avoiding obstacles on the way.
