The agreed price is less than 19% of the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion with the purchase of convertible securities, which will ensure a 10% return and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley specified that the global operation would be based on a price per unit of measure of $29, or 28% above its current change.
Morgan Stanley lost 6.79% to $23.07 each at 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said Juan Mack, the group’s CEO.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which would have to allow him to diversify his activities but he passes under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street’s biggest names to adopt much more prudent behavior than before.
The terms presented last Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan had announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japanese for nearly $8.5 billion.
" A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, explained in Tokyo, "we thought the participation would have been composed only of ordinary actions.
But in view of the current situation of the economy and the market, we have wished to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below its book value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG may convert within one year half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares if they are sold at more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at $47 or less, for a given period.
Morgan Stanley says the capitals provided by MUFG will allow him to seize investment opportunities, strengthen his balance sheet and increase his liquidity.
A spokesman for the group, however, refused to give details about the strategic projects of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should show a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan had to ease his balance since the end of August.
The last few weeks were exhausting for the group, which saw its stock market quote fall by half while the cost of security against a risk of defaults on its debt took off.
This cost backfired last Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other "survivor" of Wall Street's major investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part for Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group.
Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st-century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chavez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, for example, his colleagues and friends, is the third to put a draft for a new Constitution to the vote.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results that referred to 80% of suffrage.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were zero votes and 0.7% were blank votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, half of the suffrages plus one had to be obtained.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organization had announced a broad yes-to-yes victory, estimating it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on Sunday night to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The " Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly ", he had said, congratulating the Ecuadorians who lead the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, to be held in full calm, according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the " new socialism " advocated by the President.
The draft Constitution entails an increase in the power of the State over the economy, reserving to it the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially by the extraction of oil by foreign companies and by the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the Head of State, who will be able to hold up to two consecutive four-year terms each and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of the free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the Quito-Washington agreement for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
The 19 kidnapped people have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault against the rapists of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
All of them looked good upon their arrival at 3:30 p.m. on board a special plane to Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, to undergo medical tests, so they were unable to speak to the press.
“They are in good health” and “no ransom was paid” to the hijackers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell to the power of 35 unknown hijackers while enjoying an off-shore safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since passed from one zulu to another.
The group was made up of eleven tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous travel agency, in charge of organizing the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, carried on board two helicopters, had launched the attack the night before dawn.
"An exchange of shots occurred, and they killed half of the hijackers, the others have fled," said the official who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces were sent to Sudan from the lightning unit, where they had the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men in secret services, special forces," he said, without going into detail.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an all-terrain on board which the hijackers were on board, of which six were killed, among them the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also claimed that they were related to a Darfur rebel group, the Movement for the Liberation of Sudan-United (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by this group.
Letras - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate about the financing of culture is headlined and takes place in the current election campaign.
That's better.
But a sector of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations, or national historical sites that starve to death?
Which politician would dare to remind the federal government to neglect its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why don’t we have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage as in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government spends three and a half million euros to restore only Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in its Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected and all government departments, and all this, in concert.
In Quebec, in the Federation of History Societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers regrouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy care to search history, preserve with little money piles of private archives and preserve archaeological remains.
It is these that are often the guardian dogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and despair when promoters and responsible cast their bulldozers against our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
For when, a monument to history and heritage?
The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of the Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the US market: the three countries will support this financial and insurance institution, which also has business in Hungary, in total with 11.2 billion euros.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held higher level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s economic competition manager.
The Fortis Bank is the first to suffer from the Eurozone crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has occurred in several waves over a year ago, so the decisions made with respect to the Bank, in a sense, can be considered precedent.
According to the decision made early on Sunday, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a portion of its business, including mainly the activities – mainly insurance – purchased last year from the Dutch ABN Amr<0xC3><0xB3>.
The Fortis’ actions began a sharp decline last week and for the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree to point out that with its 85,000 employees this Bank is too large to allow it to break.
The company’s shares fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has decreased by more than two-thirds.
Looking at current stock prices, the total value of the group’s market capital is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management blamed the sharp fall in Fortis’ actions on the U.S. market insecurities in connection with the approval of the $700 billion U.S. package plan.
On Monday, the shares showed a slight increase.
On Friday, they appointed Filip Dierckx as the bank’s new CEO.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously said investors didn’t have to worry, they weren’t going to lose their money.
Among the Bank’s clients so far there was no panic, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Zorro in the Henhouse
In the U.S., life and health insurance companies when viewing drug purchase data, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy policy experts fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which in all cases links it to the use of the data of recipes to the approval of the given person.
The same must be in independent hands, because if not, "we trust the chicken to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the medical prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies depend on the price of the insurance and the amount of compensation for the health status of the customer and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Previously they sent the client to medical control and signed the contract with him knowing already the result of the control.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies the list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the diseases and health status of the customer.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of pills to lower cholesterol, it indicates that the level of fat in the blood is virtually incurably high, so it is immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a number of risks, so the insurance company besides the administration has little to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multi-use, for example certain substances serve both to treat headache and for heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk increase factor for insurance companies while the former does not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities are already obliging them to do so, although they have not received a penalty for negligence so far.
Some companies have recently also drawn up the results of laboratory tests and by combining them with drug consumption data they get more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those providing health services.
The bill that entitles the authority to control companies specialized in the supply of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such person cannot deny their approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So that the chickens, despite everything, are exposed to the good will of the fox.
Global menu of Marseille
The European Union has doubled its trade with India.
As the European Union and India are mutually trading partners, this issue, in addition to the other problems for the most part global, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been dealt with at the ninth summit that started yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU vice-president José Manuel Barroso, Commission President and Javier Solana, the main foreign policy representative, received Manmohan Singh, India’s prime minister with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, i.e. increase to more than one hundred billion euros, their trade exchange.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious objective.
Thus, they legally harmonized the existing twenty-six bilateral civil aviation agreements with India, so that air transport can also fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade treaty with the Union until the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi only ranks ninth among the EU’s trading partners.
The summit paid attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism – all forms of terrorism – and pressed for the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also tightened, although both sides have great responsibility for their failure.
The EU confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate agenda, i.e. by 2020 it wants to reduce pollutant emissions by at least 20 percent.
India also agrees with this, as at next year’s climate conference a global agreement should be reached and the production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wished to hamper the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today, the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where – at a bilateral meeting – he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>20 billion worth of orders to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports, the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
