The remains of Steve Fossett's plane, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, have been found.
The debris has been found on a 3,000-meter-high plateau in the Nevada Sierra area of Mammoth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Madera County Commissioner John Anderson has dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squad, and now we have the confirmation that it is proper to what Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance" said in a press conference.
The commissioner has specified that no human remains have been found either on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old millionaire was given death in February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (Ntsb) has reported that hours after the sighting of the remains, a team of investigators has been dispatched that has identified the device: it is owned by the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a flight.
Yesterday, always in California, not far from the Nevada border, some personal remains of Fossett have been found by a couple near their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents named Fossett, the two issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had gained a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, on the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the world tour in an aerostatic balloon: two lone weeks of flight.
Three years later he had made the world tour by plane and without scales.
Among his records, also that for having flown 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
